Area A — Search System
Issue #1: Search Only Returns Products
Problem Description
The live search feature currently queries only the products table/collection. When users search for a term, coupons, deals, and lookbooks that match the query are silently excluded from results.
What the Implementation Agent Must Inspect
•	Locate the search component (likely SearchBar.jsx or similar) and identify what API endpoint or function it calls
•	Locate the backend search handler — check if it queries a single entity type or uses a union/multi-collection approach
•	Inspect the database: are there separate tables for products, coupons, deals, and lookbooks? Are they indexed for text search?
•	Determine if the platform uses a search service (e.g., Algolia, Meilisearch, Supabase full-text search) or raw SQL/NoSQL queries
•	Check if the search results UI has slots for multiple result types or only renders product cards
Implementation Tasks
1.	Audit the search query function — identify the exact WHERE clause or filter being applied
2.	Design a multi-entity search query that fetches products, coupons, deals, and lookbooks in parallel or via union
3.	Update the search results UI to render different card types per entity (ProductCard, CouponCard, LookbookCard, DealCard)
4.	Add category labels in results (e.g., 'Products', 'Deals', 'Lookbooks') for visual separation
5.	Ensure the search modal on mobile (Issue #18) also supports this multi-entity output
Technical Considerations
•	If using Supabase: use ilike or full-text search (to_tsvector) per table and merge results in the service layer
•	If using Algolia or similar: configure a multi-index search or federated search setup
•	Rate-limit or debounce the expanded search to avoid overloading with 4x the queries per keystroke
•	Consider a result limit per entity type (e.g., 3 products, 2 deals, 2 lookbooks, 2 coupons) for clean UX


 
Area B — Product & Filter System
Issue #2: Product Visibility Bug
Problem Description
The product listing intermittently shows zero products even when products exist in the database. This is a data-fetching or filter-state bug that must be diagnosed before any other filter work proceeds.
What the Implementation Agent Must Inspect
•	Locate the product fetch function (e.g., getProducts, fetchProducts) and trace every condition applied to the query
•	Check all active filter states at page load — are default filters inadvertently excluding all products?
•	Inspect pagination logic — does page 1 always load, or can an invalid page number cause empty results?
•	Check for race conditions: is the product list reset to empty before the fetch completes, causing a visible flash of zero results?
•	Inspect the API response structure — is the product array nested incorrectly and arriving as undefined?
•	Check if any category/gender filter defaults to a value that has no products
Implementation Tasks
6.	Add console logging at every stage of the product fetch lifecycle to trace the failure path
7.	Audit all filter default values — ensure they are either 'all' or properly initialized before the first fetch
8.	Fix any race conditions by ensuring the empty state is only shown after fetch completes with confirmed zero results
9.	Add a loading skeleton state that persists until the fetch either resolves or rejects
10.	Validate API response parsing and add defensive fallback (e.g., data?.products ?? [])

Issue #3: Outfit Filters — Show Tag Counts
Problem Description
Filters on the Outfits page should display the number of outfits associated with each tag next to the tag label. For example: Streetwear (12), Minimal (5).
What the Implementation Agent Must Inspect
•	Inspect the outfits database table — does it have a tags column, or is there a separate outfit_tags junction table?
•	Check if tag counts are pre-computed anywhere or if they must be aggregated on each request
•	Inspect current filter rendering code — does it already support a count prop, or must the component be updated?
Implementation Tasks
11.	Write an aggregation query: GROUP BY tag, COUNT(*) on the outfits or outfit_tags table
12.	Return the counts alongside the tag list from the API endpoint that provides filter options
13.	Update the filter sidebar component to display counts in a muted style (e.g., gray text in parentheses)
14.	Cache or memoize counts to avoid recalculating on every filter toggle

Issue #14: Category Filters Not Updating Correctly
Problem Description
When toggling between Men, Women, and Kids gender category filters, the product list does not update correctly. This may be a state management bug or a filter query not re-executing on category change.
What the Implementation Agent Must Inspect
•	Locate the gender/category filter state — is it managed in local component state, a context, or a URL param?
•	Trace whether changing the gender filter triggers a new API call or just re-filters client-side data
•	Check for stale closure issues — is the filter value captured correctly in the async fetch function?
•	Inspect whether the filter values passed to the query match the exact values stored in the database (case sensitivity, enum values)
Implementation Tasks
15.	Ensure filter state change triggers a re-fetch with the new category value as a parameter
16.	Confirm database values for category (men, women, kids vs. Men, Women, Kids — case must match)
17.	Add a useEffect or equivalent that depends on the category filter state and re-executes the product query
18.	Test all three category combinations and verify URL params update if the system uses URL-based filters


 
Area C — UI & Layout Bugs
Issue #4: Filter Sidebar Overlaps Navbar on Scroll
Problem Description
When scrolling down the page, the filter sidebar (which is likely position: sticky) enters the navbar z-index layer and causes visual overlap.
Investigation Steps
•	Inspect the CSS/Tailwind class on the filter sidebar — confirm it uses sticky positioning
•	Check the top value set on the sticky sidebar — it must be equal to or greater than the navbar height
•	Inspect z-index values on both the navbar and sidebar — the navbar must be higher
•	Check if any overflow: hidden on a parent container is clipping the sticky behavior
Fix Instructions
•	Set top: [navbar-height]px on the sticky sidebar so it stops below the navbar
•	Ensure the navbar has a higher z-index than the sidebar (e.g., navbar z-50, sidebar z-10)
•	If a parent has overflow: hidden, remove it or restructure the container hierarchy

Issue #15: Global Background System
Problem Description
All pages except the homepage should share the same background visual style currently used on the lookbook page. This requires a global layout change.
Investigation Steps
