Instructions for the Implementation Agent
Before writing any code, the implementation agent must complete the following inspection steps in order.

Step 1: Codebase Structure Inspection
•	Map the full directory structure — identify: /components, /pages (or /app), /lib, /hooks, /api, /services, /store, /styles
•	Identify the frontend framework (Next.js, React, Vite, etc.) and styling system (Tailwind, CSS Modules, Styled Components)
•	Identify the backend: is it a Next.js API routes, a separate Express/Fastify server, or Supabase Edge Functions?
•	Identify state management: Context API, Zustand, Redux, Jotai, or none

Step 2: Database Schema Inspection
•	List all tables/collections and their columns
•	Map all foreign key relationships and junction tables
•	Identify: products, outfits, outfit_tags, lookbooks, lookbook_products, wishlist, cart_items, coupons, users, recently_viewed tables
•	Note any missing tables that must be created for the features in this document
•	Check for any existing text search indexes or full-text search configuration

Step 3: Component Inventory
•	List all page-level components and their routes
•	Identify shared layout components (Navbar, Sidebar, Footer, Layout wrapper)
•	Identify reusable UI components (ProductCard, LookbookCard, FilterPanel, Modal, etc.)
•	Note any component that could be reused or extracted during feature development

Step 4: API & Data Layer Audit
•	List all API route handlers or service functions
•	For each service function: note what table it queries, what parameters it accepts, and what it returns
•	Identify the search-related functions specifically
•	Identify cart, wishlist, and product fetch functions

Step 5: Create Implementation Plan
After completing the inspection, the agent must document its findings and create a detailed implementation plan that:
•	Confirms or corrects the assumptions made in this planning document
•	Lists the exact files that will be modified for each issue
•	Identifies any dependencies between tasks (e.g., schema must be updated before a feature can be built)
•	Estimates risk level per task (low/medium/high)

Step 6: Execute Tasks One by One
•	Follow the Implementation Roadmap sequence (Phase 1 through 17)
•	After each task: run available tests, verify the change works, then proceed
•	Do not batch unrelated changes into a single commit — one issue per implementation unit
•	Document any deviations from this plan with clear reasoning



